		 	<span id="comment_score_64230480" class="score"> (<a href="#" onclick="getModalPrefs('modcommentlog', 'Moderation Comment Log', 64230480); return false"><span class=opt>Score:</span>2</a>)</span></h4>
		</div>
		<div class="details">
			<span class="by"><span class="byby">by </span><a href="//slashdot.org/~ZipNada">ZipNada</a>  <span class="uid"><a href="//slashdot.org/~ZipNada">( 10152669 )</a></span></a></span><span class="writes" style="display:none"> writes:</span> 
			<span class="otherdetails" id="comment_otherdetails_64230480"></span>
		</div>
	</div>
	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_64230480"><p>&gt;&gt; Al is one of those metals</p><p>I didn't know that, interesting. One challenge for fusion is capturing the energy efficiently, and from what I can gather it is mostly in the form of high-energy free neutrons. In the ITER tokamak the kinetic energy would be harvested in a water jacket, and it seems like you would want the walls of the containment vessel to be very transparent to neutrons.</p><p>The neutrons decay into protons and smaller particles within about 15 minutes, so you wind up with hydrogen byproduct.</p></div>
	</div>

	<div class="commentSub" id="comment_sub_64230480">

